5.1. Basics

Let \(\alpha_{11} = \alpha_{22} = 0.1, \alpha_{12} = 0.05, \alpha_{21} = 0.01\).

  1. Determine \(N_1^∗, N_2^∗, K_1, K_2\).
  2. Draw (by hand, or in R) the ZNGIs (zero net growth isoclines); include arrows that indicate trajectories, and label the axes.
  3. Select other values for the \(\alpha\) and repeat (a) and (b); swap your answers with a friend, and check each other’s work.
  4. Start with equilibria for competing species, and show algebraically that when interspecific competition is nonexistent, species reach their carrying capacities.

  1. Start with equilibria for competing species, and show algebraically that when interspecific competition is nonexistent, species reach their carrying capacities.
    • This is simply setting the \(\alpha_{ij}\) terms to zero (or equivalently, set \(N_j\) = 0), so \(N_1^* = 1 / \alpha_{11} = K_1\) and similar for \(N_2\).
    • Oops, this is for the zero net growth isoline formulas. Instead, start with: \[N_1^* = \frac{\alpha_{22} - \alpha_{12}}{\alpha_{22} \alpha_{11} - \alpha_{12} \alpha_{21}}\] and if you set the \(\alpha_{ij}\) terms to zero, you end up with \[N_1^* = \frac{\alpha_{22}}{\alpha_{22} \alpha_{11}} = \frac{1}{\alpha_{11}}\]

5.2. Derive and simplify…

…the expression for \(N_1^∗/N_2^∗\) in terms of the \(\alpha\).

Casey’s version:

Start with the formulas for \(N_1^∗, N_2^∗\): \[\begin{align*} N_1^* &= \frac{\alpha_{22} - \alpha_{12}}{\alpha_{22} \alpha_{11} - \alpha_{12} \alpha_{21}}\\ N_2^* &= \frac{\alpha_{11} - \alpha_{21}}{\alpha_{22} \alpha_{11} - \alpha_{12} \alpha_{21}}\\ \Longrightarrow \frac{N_1^*}{N_2^*} &= \frac{\alpha_{22} - \alpha_{12}}{\alpha_{11} - \alpha_{21} \end{align*}\] … since the denominators are identical and cancel out.

5.4. Total community size

Assume for convenience that \(\alpha_{11} = \alpha_{22}\) and \(\alpha_{12} = \alpha_{21}\), and let \(N_T = N_1 + N_2\).

  1. Write \(N_T^∗\) as a function of \(\alpha_{11}, \alpha_{22}, \alpha_{12}, \alpha_{21}\). \[\begin{align*} N_T^* &= N_1^* + N_2^*\\ N_1^* &= \frac{\alpha_{22} - \alpha_{12}}{\alpha_{22} \alpha_{11} - \alpha_{12} \alpha_{21}}\\ N_2^* &= \frac{\alpha_{11} - \alpha_{21}}{\alpha_{22} \alpha_{11} - \alpha_{12} \alpha_{21}}\\ \Longrightarrow N_T^* &= \frac{\alpha_{22} - \alpha_{12} + \alpha_{11} - \alpha_{21}}{\alpha_{22} \alpha_{11} - \alpha_{12} \alpha_{21}} \end{align*}\] This doesn’t depend on the simplification described above… with that simplification: \[N_T^* = \frac{2(\alpha_{ii} - \alpha_{ij})}{\alpha_{ii}^2 - \alpha_{ij}^2} = \frac{2}{\alpha_{ii} + \alpha_{ij}}\]

  2. Describe in words how \(N_T\) varies as \(\alpha_{ij}\) varies from \(\alpha_{ii} \rightarrow 0\).

  • should this be how \(N_T^*\) varies?
    • At \(\alpha_{ii} = \alpha_{ij}\), \(N_T^* = 2/2\alpha_{ii} = K_i\). At this point, species \(i\) and \(j\) suppress each other exactly as they suppress their own populations; inter- and intra-species competition are identical, so effectively it’s identical to a single population of a species competing with itself.
    • As \(\alpha_{ij} \rightarrow 0\), \(N_T^* \rightarrow 2/\alpha_{ii} = 2K_i\). Inter-species competition becomes negligible, and it’s effectively identical to two independent species with intra-specific competition.
  1. Graph (by hand, or in R) the relation between \(N_T\) versus \(\alpha_{ij}\). Let \(\alpha_{ii} = 0.01\).
a_ii <- 0.01
tmp_df <- data.frame(a_ij = seq(0, a_ii, a_ii/20),
                     a_ii) %>%
  mutate(N_T_star = 2 / (a_ii + a_ij))

ggplot(tmp_df, aes(x = a_ij, y = N_T_star)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0) + geom_vline(xintercept = 0) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = (1:2)/a_ii, linetype = 'dashed') +
  labs(x = latex2exp::TeX('$\alpha_{ij}$'),
       y = latex2exp::TeX('$N_T^*$')) +
  theme_minimal()

5.5. Interpret the Routh-Hurwitz criterion…

…in terms of species relative inter- and intraspecific competitive abilities.

Casey’s attempt:

The Routh-Hurwitz criterion states that “a two-species equilibrium will be locally stable, only if \(\mathbf{J}_{11} + \mathbf{J}_{22} < 0\) and if \(\mathbf{J}_{11} \mathbf{J}_{22} − \mathbf{J}_{12} \mathbf{J}_{21} > 0\),” where the Jacobian \(\mathbf J\) is:

\[\begin{align*} \mathbf{J} = \begin{pmatrix} \frac{\partial \dot N_1}{\partial N_1} & \frac{\partial \dot N_1}{\partial N_2} \\ \frac{\partial \dot N_2}{\partial N_1} & \frac{\partial \dot N_2}{\partial N_2} \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} r_1 - 2r_1 \alpha_{11} N_1 - r_1 \alpha_{12} N_2 & -r_1 \alpha_{12} N_1 \\ -r_2 \alpha_{21} N_2 & r_2 - 2r_2 \alpha_{22} N_2 - r_2 \alpha_{21} N_1 \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}\]

5.6. The Jacobian matrix

Here we turn words into math. Note that this is one way of making our assumptions very precise and clear. In each case below (a.–d.), (i) use algebraic inequalities between the \(\beta\)s and between the \(\alpha\)s to show what the assumptions imply for the equalities and inequalities with respect to all \(\alpha\)s, (ii) use these inequalities to simplify the Jacobian matrix (eq. (5.21) as much as possible, (iii) show algebraically how these (in)equalities determine the sign of each element of the Jacobian, and (iv) explain in words how the magnitudes of the Jacobian elements determine stability properties.

  1. Assume that both species are functionally equivalent, and intraspecific competition is more intense than interspecific competition.
  2. Assume species are functionally equivalent and that each species has a greater impact on each other than they do on themselves.
  3. Assume species are functionally equivalent and interspecific competition is precisely equal to intraspecific competition.
  4. Assume species have the same carrying capacity, and can coexist, but that species 1 is dominant.
  5. Assume species 1 is the better competitor (note: this may have multiple interpretations).
  6. Assume species 1 and 2 are equivalent (note: this may have multiple interpretations).
